My teams currently dependent on a small handful of people when it comes to 3D printing parts, so I’m trying to develop a few lessons for people on how to design for 3D printed parts, how to use a 3D printer, and understanding their limits, etc.

How do your teams typically design for 3D printed parts? What filaments do you use for different applications? Any other info that might be useful?

Edit: What do you do to account for 3D Printing fumes as well? I know most people don’t worry about it too much, but having 6 printers in one small room without great ventilation myself, it’s something I probably need to look into.

We generally prefer to use PLA or tough PLA in our robot because the PLA material is both cheap and easy and fast to print. You can choose to use TPU filament in wheel-like applications, but be careful because TPU must be printed slowly.

There are many tips to be found here and elsewhere online.

I mostly use PETG for anything non-decorative. I find that, for me, it strikes the right balance between strong and non-toxic while not being too temperamental. I also use TPU.

FDM is laminar, so parts are weakest in the Z-direction and will fail by layer separation. Infill doesn’t add much strength; you’re better adding perimeters and making selected areas solid.

A lot of my design work is concerned with making parts FDM printable with no or few supports. Organic supports are much easier to remove than the older type. Careful use of a heat gun can help to smooth surfaces; it really helps to get a heat gun where you can set the temperature.

When appropriate, lubricate your 3-D printed parts. Almost any lubricant will work. (WD40 is not a lubricant.)

Right now we use a mixture of PLA, PETG, TPU, and Nylon-CF (all Overture Filament) for different applications, using a number of FDM printers.

-PLA for spacers and stuff like that
-PETG we don’t use to often but is a little stronger than PLA
-TPU for things like hard stops to protect mechs from hitting the bot/ provide cushion (might try testing some TPU tread over the summer for swerve)
-Nylon-CF for parts we need to be strong and heat resistant such as pulleys, etc.

I’ve found somewhere in the range of 20-40% to be the sweet spot for infill.

Some tips I learned throughout 2023 and 2024 seasons for designing all our 3dp parts are:

-When designing flat sides, chamfer the edges rather than filleting. This will prevent super steep overhangs that can potentially ruin bed adhesion or quality, and generally looks nicer.

-Design with tolerance for stuff like bolts, usually a tolerance of 0 will make something press fit and for stuff like holes, you can usually add 10 thou of clearance (depending on how dialed in your printer is).

-While heat-set inserts do work, I’ve grown to love press-fit locknuts inside parts. This makes it easy to install, and you don’t need to carry separate inserts.

-Adding cable strain releif and small slots for zipties can go a long way to making something comp ready. You can also add stuff like a lens guard for protecting cameras on camera mounts.

-Design with simplicity in mind. If possible avoid needing multiple parts that bolt together, (you can also try snap fit) and design so that the parts are easy to print with minimal supports.

In terms of filament, we use Eryone CF-PETG with great success. It’s cheap, strong-enough, and prints really cleanly, but make sure you use a hardened nozzle.

I used PETG for our pivot gears this year and it worked great, but they had some pretty big teeth as well. For smaller gears I’d more recommend something like ABS, ASA, or Nylon. They’re stronger and more temp resistant. We had a couple of problems with the PETG gears in our swerve failing in the past.

Ive got a few tips from printing. Supports are not your friends unless your using a markforged printer. PLA should not be used for anything critical (gears, pulleys, etc). Use PET, PETG, ABS, PA, ASA. All of those are good and have thier own advantages. Fillets should be used whenever you have a large difference between sizes (think gears to shafts). Itterate, Itterate, Itterate, your printer will be able to work by itself meaning that your able to get so many more designs off. Use metal when you can, threads, metal, hex holes, metal. I personally have had great luck with using expanding inserts and heatpressing them into my parts. This provides both advantages and has lead to little/no slipping. Hex stock (1/2in od 3/8in id) for hex holes are incredibly useful to avoid rounding out your holes.

We found CF-PETG is more than strong enough for anything we’re printing.
We tend to avoid printing stuff like gears or anything heavily loaded as usually it would be better machined.

In terms of why not Nylon-CF, it comes down to price and the fact that Nylon-CF is extremely hard to get printing reliably. When the team is waiting on your prints to start testing, or printing overnight, you do not want to be dealing with the potential for failure or warping.

We use a Bambu P1S and have had poor luck with CF-Nylons (PA6) in the past. Not to mention the CF-PETG is a third the price
